\section{Resolving browser URLs}

SharePoint's REST API does not work with the browser URLs directly. The REST
endpoints want two pieces of information instead:

\begin{description}
\item[site URL] The site root used for [[_api/contextinfo]] and the REST base.
\item[server-relative path] The file path starting at the SharePoint host,
  such as [[/personal/user/Documents/file.txt]].
\end{description}

We bundle those two values in a small immutable object.
<<classes>>=
@dataclasses.dataclass(frozen=True)
class SharePointLocation:
  """Resolved SharePoint address for one file or folder."""

  site_url: str
  server_relative_path: str

  <<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>
@

The local file name comes from the last path component. That is the right
default for [[get]], because downloading to the remote file name mirrors common
shell tools and avoids inventing yet another naming convention.
<<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>=
@property
def name(self):
  """Return the file name part of the resolved path."""
  return pathlib.PurePosixPath(self.server_relative_path).name
@

Uploads need the containing folder separately from the file name, since
SharePoint's [[Files/add]] endpoint addresses the folder and the new file name
independently.
<<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>=
@property
def folder_relative_path(self):
  """Return the parent folder of the resolved file path."""
  return str(pathlib.PurePosixPath(self.server_relative_path).parent)
@

Listings address the owning document library and then select one folder inside
it. The library root is therefore the first three path components of the
server-relative path.
<<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>=
@property
def library_relative_path(self):
  """Return the document-library root for the resolved path."""
  parts = self.server_relative_path.lstrip("/").split("/")
  if len(parts) < 3:
    raise ValueError("SharePoint path does not contain a document library")
  return "/" + "/".join(parts[:3])
@

