\section{SharePoint REST endpoints}

The session methods use SharePoint's classic REST endpoints for file transfers
and the list-view endpoint for folder listings, all with the same shared
cookie-based authentication. The classic REST URLs embed paths inside OData
string literals, so single quotes inside names must be escaped.
<<functions>>=
def _escape_odata_string(value: str) -> str:
  """Return ``value`` escaped for an OData string literal."""
  return value.replace("'", "''")
@

For downloads we can address the exact file and ask for [[/$value]], which
returns the file bytes rather than metadata.
<<functions>>=
def _download_url(location: SharePointLocation) -> str:
  """Return the REST endpoint for downloading ``location``."""
  path = _escape_odata_string(location.server_relative_path)
  return (
      f"{location.site_url}/_api/web/"
      f"GetFileByServerRelativeUrl('{path}')/$value")
@

Uploads use the containing folder plus a file name. This lets SharePoint create
the file when needed and overwrite it when requested.
<<functions>>=
def _upload_url(location: SharePointLocation, overwrite: bool) -> str:
  """Return the REST endpoint for uploading to ``location``."""
  folder = _escape_odata_string(location.folder_relative_path)
  name = _escape_odata_string(location.name)
  return (
      f"{location.site_url}/_api/web/"
      f"GetFolderByServerRelativeUrl('{folder}')/"
      f"Files/add(url='{name}',overwrite={str(overwrite).lower()})")
@

Listings use a different SharePoint endpoint. Shared personal OneDrive folders
can deny [[GetFolderByServerRelativeUrl(...)/Folders]] and [[.../Files]] even
after authentication, while the browser still renders them through
[[RenderListDataAsStream]]. We therefore ask the owning document library to
render the target folder as a list view instead of calling the denied child
collection endpoints directly.
<<functions>>=
def _render_list_data_url(location: SharePointLocation) -> str:
  """Return the list-view endpoint for listing ``location``."""
  list_url = urllib.parse.quote(
      f"'{_escape_odata_string(location.library_relative_path)}'",
      safe="")
  return (
      f"{location.site_url}/_api/web/"
      f"GetList(@listUrl)/RenderListDataAsStream?@listUrl={list_url}")
@

<<functions>>=
def _render_list_data_body(location: SharePointLocation) -> dict:
  """Return the list-view request payload for listing ``location``."""
  return {
      "parameters": {
          "RenderOptions": LIST_DATA_RENDER_OPTIONS,
          "AddRequiredFields": True,
          "FolderServerRelativeUrl": location.server_relative_path,
      }
  }
@

SharePoint does not always redirect unauthenticated users straight into the KTH
login flow. It often returns [[403]] with an [[X-Forms_Based_Auth_Required]]
header that points at the real entry page. That header can depend on the exact
endpoint: a browser folder URL, the old [[/Folders]] endpoint, and
[[RenderListDataAsStream]] for the same folder need not agree. If we keep
retrying a broader site URL, or even the wrong browser URL, [[UGlogin]] only
sees the same forbidden response and recurses forever. We therefore probe the
actual SharePoint endpoint first and only fall back to [[location.site_url]]
when that endpoint does not expose a forms-auth trigger.
<<functions>>=
def _login_trigger_url(url: str, location: SharePointLocation) -> str:
  """Return the best login trigger URL for ``location``."""
  for probe_url in (url, location.site_url):
    logger.debug("Probing SharePoint auth trigger via %s", probe_url)
    try:
      response = requests.get(probe_url,
                              allow_redirects=False,
                              timeout=LOGIN_TRIGGER_TIMEOUT)
    except requests.RequestException as exc:
      logger.debug("SharePoint auth trigger probe failed for %s: %s",
                   probe_url,
                   exc)
      continue

    trigger_url = response.headers.get("X-Forms_Based_Auth_Required")
    logger.debug("SharePoint auth trigger probe status %s for %s",
                 response.status_code,
                 probe_url)
    if trigger_url:
      logger.debug("Using SharePoint forms-auth trigger %s", trigger_url)
      return trigger_url

  logger.debug("Falling back to site URL %s as auth trigger",
               location.site_url)
  return location.site_url
@

This probe is only about discovering the right login entry point, so a short
timeout is enough.
<<constants>>=
LOGIN_TRIGGER_TIMEOUT = 15
@

Those URLs are pure string transformations, which makes them cheap and useful
to test in isolation.
