We reuse the package's normal logging configuration, but keep a module logger so
that the global CLI verbosity flags can expose focused OneDrive diagnostics.
<<constants>>=
logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
@

The shared session already knows how to handle KTH's Ladok SSO and Microsoft
Authenticator pages. SharePoint adds two missing hops: the Azure AD federated
sign-in screen (which Microsoft serves as a JavaScript page that none of the
existing handlers can drive), and the generic KTH SAML relay plus the
[[UGlogin]] handler used by services behind [[login.ug.kth.se]].

We attach those handlers lazily per site. That keeps the constructor simple and
lets the same session talk to both personal OneDrive hosts and ordinary
SharePoint sites. The trigger URL comes from [[_login_trigger_url()]] using
the exact SharePoint endpoint we are about to call, so the forms-auth header
can steer [[UGlogin]] into a real login page.

[[MicrosoftLogin]] is added first so it can intercept the Azure AD
[[oauth2/authorize]] page before [[UGlogin]] sees it. Without that ordering,
[[UGlogin]] misclassifies the JavaScript sign-in page as \enquote{already
authenticated}, replays the original failing request, and loops. The
[[domain_hint]] points at KTH's federated domain so Azure AD redirects
straight to [[login.ug.kth.se]] where [[SAMLlogin]] and [[UGlogin]] take over.

[[UGlogin]] needs a [[base_url]] for two related checks. First,
[[need_login]] only treats a 401/403 as our concern when the failing URL
belongs to our service; without [[base_url]] it falls back to a substring
check for [[kth.se]], which never matches SharePoint hosts such as
[[kth-my.sharepoint.com]]. Second, on the final redirect to
[[login.ug.kth.se]], [[need_login]] only claims the redirect when one of
the URLs in [[response.history]] starts with [[base_url]]; SharePoint's
forms-auth bootstrap goes through [[/_forms/default.aspx]] on the host
root, never through the personal-site path itself. The SharePoint host
root (for example [[https://kth-my.sharepoint.com]]) satisfies both
conditions.

The trigger URL is more specific than the host root, and sometimes more
specific than the browser URL itself. SharePoint can hand out different
forms-auth entry points for different file, folder, or REST endpoints, and
[[UGlogin]] treats that trigger as part of its configuration. Because the
underlying [[ladok3]] browser session is shared, a file download and a later
folder listing on the same SharePoint host would otherwise accumulate two
different [[UGlogin]] handlers with the same [[base_url]] but different trigger
URLs. [[AutologinSession]] runs handlers in insertion order, so the stale one
would keep claiming the host and bootstrapping the wrong page. We therefore
refresh any existing SharePoint-scoped [[UGlogin]] for the same host root
before adding the current one.
<<[[OneDriveSession]] methods>>=
def _ensure_login_handlers(self, url: str, location: SharePointLocation):
  """Attach the KTH web-login handlers needed for ``location``."""
  if self.__username is None or self.__password is None:
    logger.debug("Skipping login handlers for %s because credentials are "
                 "unavailable",
                 location.site_url)
    return

  login_trigger_url = _login_trigger_url(url, location)
  parsed_site = urllib.parse.urlsplit(location.site_url)
  site_host_root = f"{parsed_site.scheme}://{parsed_site.netloc}"
  logger.debug("Ensuring SharePoint login handlers for %s", location.site_url)
  logger.debug("UGlogin trigger URL is %s", login_trigger_url)
  logger.debug("UGlogin base URL is %s", site_host_root)
  <<refresh SharePoint [[UGlogin]] handlers for this host>>
  self.__session.add_handler(
      weblogin.microsoft.MicrosoftLogin(domain_hint=AZURE_AD_DOMAIN_HINT))
  self.__session.add_handler(weblogin.kth.SAMLlogin(rerun_requests=True))
  self.__session.add_handler(
      weblogin.kth.UGlogin(self.__username,
                           self.__password,
                            login_trigger_url=login_trigger_url,
                            base_url=site_host_root,
                            rerun_requests=True))
@

We only want one SharePoint-scoped [[UGlogin]] per host root. The session API
lets us append handlers, but not replace them, so we prune stale ones directly
from the underlying handler list before we add the current configuration.
<<refresh SharePoint [[UGlogin]] handlers for this host>>=
handlers = getattr(self.__session, "_AutologinSession__handlers", None)
if handlers is None:
  handlers = getattr(self.__session, "handlers", None)
if handlers is not None:
  stale_handlers = []
  for handler in handlers:
    if not isinstance(handler, weblogin.kth.UGlogin):
      continue
    handler_base_url = getattr(handler, "base_url", None)
    if handler_base_url is None:
      handler_base_url = getattr(handler, "_UGlogin__base_url", None)
    if handler_base_url == site_host_root:
      stale_handlers.append(handler)
  if stale_handlers:
    logger.debug("Refreshing %s SharePoint UGlogin handler(s) for %s",
                 len(stale_handlers),
                 site_host_root)
    handlers[:] = [handler for handler in handlers
                   if handler not in stale_handlers]
@

