\section{The command-line interface}

The CLI just bridges local files, folder listings, and the session object
above. We keep it thin so the real behaviour stays testable through ordinary
Python methods.
<<option and argument definitions>>=
url_arg = typer.Argument(help="SharePoint or OneDrive browser URL to a file.")
folder_url_arg = typer.Argument(help="SharePoint or OneDrive browser URL to a "
                                     "folder.")
output_arg = typer.Argument(help="Local output path. Defaults to the remote "
                                 "file name.")
local_path_arg = typer.Argument(help="Local file to upload.",
                                exists=True,
                                dir_okay=False,
                                readable=True,
                                resolve_path=True)
overwrite_opt = typer.Option("--overwrite/--no-overwrite",
                             help="Replace an existing remote file.")
@

The [[get]] command stores the file in the current directory when no explicit
output path is provided. That makes the common case concise while still letting
callers choose another local path when needed.
<<command definitions>>=
@cli.command(name="get")
def cli_get(url: Annotated[str, url_arg],
            output: Annotated[Optional[pathlib.Path], output_arg] = None):
  """Download a file from OneDrive or SharePoint."""
  location = parse_sharepoint_url(url)
  if output is None:
    output = pathlib.Path(location.name)
  logger.debug("Writing downloaded file to %s", output)
  output.write_bytes(OneDriveSession().get_by_url(url))
@

The [[ls]] command is deliberately non-recursive. It prints one tab-separated
line per child entry so the output stays readable to humans and easy to feed
into shell tools.
<<command definitions>>=
@cli.command(name="ls")
def cli_ls(url: Annotated[str, folder_url_arg]):
  """List the direct contents of a OneDrive or SharePoint folder."""
  for kind, name in OneDriveSession().list_by_url(url):
    print(f"{kind}\t{name}")
@

For [[put]] the caller already has the local file, so the command only needs to
read its bytes and forward them together with the remote URL.
<<command definitions>>=
@cli.command(name="put")
def cli_put(local_path: Annotated[pathlib.Path, local_path_arg],
            url: Annotated[str, url_arg],
            overwrite: Annotated[bool, overwrite_opt] = True):
  """Upload a local file to OneDrive or SharePoint."""
  logger.debug("Reading local upload payload from %s", local_path)
  OneDriveSession().put_by_url(url,
                               local_path.read_bytes(),
                               overwrite=overwrite)
